Why Jerome Powell Has to Go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as the head of the US Federal Reserve – essentially the most powerful position within the world economy?
A wrong choice here could have grave consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to adequately regulate the banking system, setting the stage for the worst economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political leaders' response to it had far-reaching political consequences; it exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting sense of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are many clichés why the current central bank chief Jerome Powell should be confirmed in office.
It would be a testament to non-partisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
We need someone with experience to lead us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
I have heard exactly the same arguments 25 years ago, when I was chairman of President Bill Clinton's economic advisory staff and the confirmation of Greenspan was an issue.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country paid a heavy price for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and refused him a second term after Volcker had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed a lot to Volcker, but he sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an adherent of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful evaluation and sensitivity to goal conflicts are required.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that markets alone are efficient, stable, fair, and competitive?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the US have always had clearly articulated but distinctly different views on these issues (at least until Republicans succumbed to populist fantasies).
In my view, the Democrats rightly worry about the consequences of unemployment.
The crisis of 2008 showed that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
In addition, we know that traditionally, only under tight labor markets do marginalized groups enter the economy and wage gaps are reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a test for every US central bank chief.
The US is already facing difficult decisions about what to do against inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially problems stemming from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed consider the unemployment rate among African Americans, who have not yet regained their pre-pandemic levels?
Would interest rate hikes (and thus an increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While mispricing mortgage-backed securities was at the center of the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of even more widespread and severe mispricing related to assets associated with climate change.
What should the Fed do about this?
Powell is not the man for the job.
Initially, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump and thereby risked the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action regarding climate risk, despite other central bankers around the world having already declared this to be the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate questions do not fall within the mandate of the Fed, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such laxity is the last thing the economy needs right now.
A glaring competition failure and the lack of adequate regulation already allow for excessive profits, reduce credit availability for small businesses, and give dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators praise Powell for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
But any second-year student would know that you cannot tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates during a recession.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argued, Powell does not feel particularly committed to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve regarding monetary policy tightening over the past decade was characterized by a series of misjudgments that go back to the "Taper Tantrum" in 2013.
While many observers of the Fed insist that inequality is not the bank's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policy has significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as raising interest rates too soon can choke growth, weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for greater market concentration.
Finally, the recent scandal involving stock trades by leading Fed representatives has undermined trust in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparent lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including those related to managing some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has long troubled me.
After four years of Trump weakening trust in US institutions, there now exists a real risk that trust in the integrity of the central bank will further suffer.
No Fed representative should need an ethics officer deciding when certain stock market transactions would appear improper.
The Fed is somewhat akin to the US Supreme Court.
This is supposed to stand above politics, but at least since Bush v. Gore, we know that is not the case.
Trump has made this clear for anyone who still had doubts.
Also, the Fed is supposed to be independent, yet Powell and Greenspan, by following their party's deregulation agenda, clearly showed that this is also not the case.
While the Federal Reserve makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, power traditionally concentrates in the hands of the Fed chair – much more so than in the hands of the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the Fed chair who decides what gets brought to a vote and which topics are postponed or pushed forward.
The climate issue is just one example where it is crucial who sits at the head of the table.
The United States need a central bank that truly commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitive financial sector.
Those who believe we can rely on unbridled markets or that regulation has already gone too far lack insight.
We do not need an ideologue like Greenspan or a Wall Street-leaning lawyer like Powell.
What is needed is someone with deep economic understanding and who shares Biden’s values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are certainly many people who meet these criteria.
But Biden does not have to look far to find someone whose abilities have already been proven.
Lael Brainard already sits on the Federal Reserve, where she has demonstrated her expertise and won market confidence – without compromising on her values.
Biden can have both: a Fed chair who maintains continuity and does not disrupt the markets, but shares his economic and social program.
